  "prompt": "When should I prune my roses?",
  "response": "Pruning roses is essential for maintaining their health, shape, and encouraging abundant blooms. The best time to prune roses depends on the climate and the type of rose, but here are some general guidelines:\n\n### **When to Prune Roses**\n1. **Late Winter or Early Spring**  \n   - This is the most common time to prune roses, just as new growth begins to emerge.  \n   - In colder climates, prune when the threat of hard frost has passed but before the plant breaks dormancy.  \n   - Look for swelling buds or small red shoots as a sign that it\u2019s time to prune.\n\n2. **Fall Pruning (Optional)**  \n   - In areas with harsh winters, light pruning in late fall can help prevent wind damage and reduce the risk of disease.  \n   - Avoid heavy pruning in fall, as it can stimulate new growth that may be damaged by cold weather.\n\n3. **After Blooming (for certain types)**  \n   - Some roses, like ramblers and once-blooming varieties, should be pruned right after they finish flowering.  \n\n### **What to Prune**\n- **Dead or Diseased Wood:** Remove any dead, damaged, or diseased canes.  \n- **Crossing or Rubbing Branches:** Cut back branches that rub against each other to prevent wounds and disease.  \n- **Shape and Size:** Trim to maintain the desired shape and encourage bushy growth.  \n- **Thin Out Old Canes:** For mature plants,\u8fd9\u4e00\u5207\u53d6\u51b3\u4e8e\u526a\u6389\u4e00\u4e9b\u8001\u830e\u4ee5\u4fc3\u8fdb\u65b0\u751f\u957f\u3002\n\n### **Tips for Pruning**\n- Use clean, sharp pruning shears to make clean cuts.  \n- Cut at a 45-degree angle, about 1/4 inch above an outward-facing bud to encourage outward growth.  \n- Remove weak or spindly growth to direct energy to stronger canes.\n\nBy pruning at the right time and in the right way, you\u2019ll help your rose bushes thrive and produce beautiful blooms throughout the growing season!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
